        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nehemiah 12:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nehemiah 10:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Seraiah and Azariah are priests who sealed the covenant with Nehemiah the Tirshatha, about seventy years later. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nehemiah 12:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " shows that Seraiah was the name of a priestly clan. Perhaps the name Seraiah should be read in the present passage before, or instead of, Azariah. (Comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1Chronicles 6:13-14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".) If, however, the name is official, not personal, like the names in the preceding verse, this supposition is hardly necessary. Either Azariah or Seraiah might equally represent the priestly house intended.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
